            number: 2,
            title: "Track the Emotion, Not Just the Transaction",
            description: "For 30 days, log not just what you spend but what you were feeling before, during, and after significant financial transactions. Note purchases that gave you a brief emotional lift followed by regret. Note moments of financial paralysis when decision-making shut down. Note the feeling of your checking account balance — what emotional state it puts you in. This emotional ledger is more informative than a spending ledger, because it reveals the affective drivers of financial behavior."
          },
          {
            number: 3,
            title: "Automate the High-Stakes Decisions",
            description: "For any financial behavior where psychology consistently overrides intention — saving, investing, debt repayment — remove the psychology from the equation through automation. Set up automatic transfers to savings the day after payday, automatic investment contributions, automatic debt payments. The research on present bias and behavioral finance consistently shows that the most effective financial change comes from structural design that bypasses psychological resistance rather than from willpower-based attempts to override it repeatedly."
          },
          {
            number: 4,
            title: "Redesign Your Reference Group",
            description: "Given the research on social comparison and status spending, deliberately audit your social environment. Who are the people you most compare yourself to financially? What media content creates financial comparison anxiety? Reducing your exposure to conspicuous wealth displays — whether from social media, certain peer groups, or certain neighborhoods — measurably reduces status spending. Replace financial comparison with financial mentorship: find one or two people who have built the kind of financial life you want and study their actual behaviors, not their displayed wealth."
          },
          {
            number: 5,
            title: "Build a New Financial Identity Through Small Wins",
            description: "Identity changes through evidence, not declaration. Rather than trying to convince yourself you are a wealthy person or a good financial manager through affirmations, generate actual evidence through small, consistent behaviors: saving a fixed amount every week without fail, investing a small regular sum, paying off one small debt completely. Each successful execution of a new financial behavior is a vote for a new financial identity. The evidence accumulates into a new self-narrative over months and years."
          },
